cientific knowledge for its forthcoming. Major suppliers of scientific knowledge are the researchers themselves, science communicators and science journalists - each of which choose their very own approaches to selection, presentation and communication of science, often depending on the target group. Although different in their goals and approaches, digital media in particular has led to great overlaps which result in interwoven relationships equally affecting both external and internal forms of science communication. This edited book describes, quantifies and critically discusses the interplay between publisher- and journalism-driven science communication and its effect on the scholarly communication system, especially on the measures of impact evaluation. It is of major interest to researchers from science of science, bibliometrics, science communication, and journalism studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBibliometrie. 4aInformation Science. 4aWissenschaftskommunikation. 4aWissenschaftspublizistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Library & Information Science / General.2bisacsh  aScience communication.  abibliometrics.  ascholarly communication.  ascience journalism.1 aBrede, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroer, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroer, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCostas, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehmkuhl, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeidecker-Sandmann, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela